  "prompt": "When the Night King's White Walkers take children, do they become fully grown like those at end of the Game of Thrones episode \"Oathbreaker?\"",
  "response": "In the **Game of Thrones** TV series, when the White Walkers (also known as the Others) capture and kill individuals\u2014whether adults or children\u2014they typically reanimate them as **wights**. These wights retain the physical appearance they had at the moment of death, meaning that children taken by the White Walkers do **not** transform into fully grown adults. Instead, they return to life as undead beings, maintaining their original size and characteristics from when they were killed.\n\nRegarding the specific episode you mentioned, **\"Oathbreaker\"**, it's important to clarify that this title isn't an official episode name from the main **Game of Thrones** series. You might be referring to a particular scene or possibly another piece of media related to the franchise. However, based on the canonical content of the series up to its conclusion in October 2023:\n\n- **Children Taken by White Walkers:** There are no instances in the series where children abducted by the White Walkers grow into fully mature undead beings upon their transformation. The reanimation process maintains their age and physical state at death.\n\n- **Wights' Appearance:** Throughout the series, wights generally appear as they did in life, albeit decayed and animated by dark magic. There are no canonical examples of wights undergoing significant physical growth post-transformation.\n\nIt's possible that scenes or fan interpretations might suggest variations, but based on the official narrative, the transformation preserves the individual's state at death without accelerating their aging or causing them to grow into adults if they were children at the time.\n\nIf you're referencing a specific moment or a different adaptation (such as a book or a fan-made project) where children are shown becoming fully grown wights, please provide more details, and I can offer a more targeted explanation.",
